The sight of women crying reminds me of eating cigars….

I was never a video game person. 

In fact I’m fairly certain I’ve never beaten any video game without the help of GameGenie®, maybe Mike Tyson’s Punch Out once… either way; very few video games had much impact on me but a select few did make their mark. One of few was GoldenEye 007 for N64. I never owned the game or the game system, but every day for about 4 months in 1997 I would skate over to my buddy’s house and attempt to beat my friends in multiplayer mode.

And even if god was on my side and I was able to score the RC-P90 I would rarely find myself anywhere but 4th place, being slapped to death by Oddjob. This meant I spent a lot of time flipping through skate mags and scoring snacks from the kitchen. And while I’ll always cherish being murdered by my friends every afternoon, it was these mundane trips to the fridge where I would encounter the most enduring memories… because we we’re not alone in the house on these afternoons. My friend’s dad was always there, he either worked at night or never worked at all, I’m not sure. But what I am sure of is that every day… Every single day I was there, his dad sat in the same chair in the same position, not saying a word, and ate a box of cigars. 

He did not smoke them, he did not light them, he did not merely chew them. He would sit in his chair, turn on the most dramatic soap operas I had ever seen, shows that seemed to have no dialogue at all and only scorned women hysterically weeping, and he would open a cheap box of cigars and eat them all. A new box of cigars and the same women crying, everyday. 

We never said a word to each other, but one time I came in while I was eating a slim jim and he gave me a nod.

One of the few things that consistently brings me joy is making these annual lists of all my top jams from the past year and sharing it with a few people who care and a ton that don’t. So here it is! My favorite music of 2023! Link to the full year end playlist in my bio. Let me know what you think. This tradition started almost 10 years ago between me and my fellow musical optimist @vacationsonline who always manages to find things I missed. Please go listen to his lists as well. As bad as it gets, the jams will always help you through. I love you. - Blaise
